{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585921"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:22:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:22:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15035"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15035"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.17,0.09,0.43,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7723"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116268"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7723"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98264"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"10486"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18863"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18866"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116268"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute tubular necrosis is a condition where damage to the renal tubular epithelial cells leads to kidney dysfunction. Laboratory findings typically show elevated serum creatinine and reduced urine output.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism causing reduced urine output in acute tubular necrosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tubular backleak of filtrate","Interstitial inflammation","Afferent arteriole vasoconstriction","Tubular epithelial cell death","Basement membrane disruption"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn acute tubular necrosis, \u003Cstrong\u003Etubular backleak of filtrate\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when damaged tubular epithelial cells allow filtered fluid to leak back into the bloodstream. This directly reduces urine output as less filtrate reaches the collecting ducts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterstitial inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E may occur but does not directly cause reduced urine output. \u003Cstrong\u003EAfferent arteriole vasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E can contribute to reduced glomerular filtration rate but is not the primary mechanism. \u003Cstrong\u003ETubular epithelial cell death\u003C/strong\u003E is the underlying pathology but does not directly cause reduced urine output. \u003Cstrong\u003EBasement membrane disruption\u003C/strong\u003E may occur but is not the primary mechanism reducing urine output.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional mechanisms contributing to reduced urine output include tubular obstruction from cellular debris and cast formation, which increases intratubular pressure and reduces glomerular filtration rate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tubular backleak in acute tubular necrosis allows filtrate to leak back into the bloodstream through damaged tubular epithelium","Decreased glomerular filtration rate in acute tubular necrosis results from tubular obstruction and increased intratubular pressure","Cast formation and cellular debris contribute to tubular obstruction in acute tubular necrosis"],"references":["Singh P, Okusa MD. The role of tubuloglomerular feedback in the pathogenesis of acute kidney injury. Contrib Nephrol. 2011;174:12-21. doi: 10.1159/000329229. Epub 2011 Sep 9. PMID: 21921605.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98264"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15035"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98264"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T03:02:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T03:02:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7723"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116268"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emed